{"lemma":"عامِرٌ","slug":"عامِرٌ","root":"ع.م.ر","root_slug":"ع-م-ر","root_link":"/words/roots/ع-م-ر","pos":"ADJ","pos_camel":"adj","paradigm":[],"frequency_in_corpus":0,"cross_references":{"qac":{"found":false},"wiktextract":{"found":true,"entry_count":2,"pos_tags":["adj","name"],"has_etymology":true,"sense_count":6},"lanes":{"found":true,"entry_ids":["n30534"],"search_url":"https://lanelexicon.com/?s=%D8%B9%D8%A7%D9%85%D9%90%D8%B1%D9%8C"}},"translations":null,"definition":{"source":"wiktextract","senses":[{"pos":"adj","gloss":"inhabited, peopled, populated"},{"pos":"adj","gloss":"populous"},{"pos":"adj","gloss":"crowded, filled"},{"pos":"adj","gloss":"civilized, flourishing, thriving"},{"pos":"adj","gloss":"cultivated (land)"},{"pos":"name","gloss":"a male given name, Amir or Aamir"}]},"etymology":{"source":"wiktextract","text":"Derived from the active participle of the verb عَمُرَ (ʕamura, “to be inhabited, be cultivated”)."},"ipa":["/ʕaː.mir/"],"lanes_definition":{"source":"lanes","entries":[{"entry_id":"n30534","headword_ar":"عَامِرٌ","root":"Emr","body":[{"kind":"italic_en","text":"Living long."},{"kind":"text","text":"(Msb, TA.) ―         -b2-"},{"kind":"italic_en","text":"Remaining, continuing, staying, residing, dwelling,"},{"kind":"text","text":"or"},{"kind":"italic_en","text":"abiding,"},{"kind":"text","text":"in a place: (TA:) and thus, or"},{"kind":"italic_en","text":"remaining,"},{"kind":"text","text":"&c.,"},{"kind":"italic_en","text":"and congregated,"},{"kind":"text","text":"in a pl. sense. (Mus'ab, O.) [Hence,]"},{"kind":"italic_en","text":"An inhabitant"},{"kind":"text","text":"of a house: pl."},{"kind":"arabic","text_bw":"Eum~aArN","text_ar":"عُمَّارٌ"},{"kind":"text","text":". (TA.) And"},{"kind":"arabic","text_bw":"Eum~aAru Albuyuwti","text_ar":"عُمَّارُ البُيُوتِ"},{"kind":"italic_en","text":"The jinn,"},{"kind":"text","text":"or"},{"kind":"italic_en","text":"genii, that inhabit houses."},{"kind":"text","text":"(S.) And"},{"kind":"arabic","text_bw":"EawaAmiru Albuyuwti","text_ar":"عَوَامِرُ البُيُوتِ"},{"kind":"italic_en","text":"The serpents that are in houses:"},{"kind":"text","text":"sing."},{"kind":"arabic","text_bw":"EaAmirN","text_ar":"عَامِرٌ"},{"kind":"text","text":"and"},{"kind":"arabic","text_bw":"EaAmirapN","text_ar":"عَامِرَةٌ"},{"kind":"text","text":": accord. to some, they are so called because of the length of their lives. (TA.) ―         -b3-  See also"},{"kind":"arabic","text_bw":"muEotamirN","text_ar":"مُعْتَمِرٌ"},{"kind":"text","text":".       -A2-  Also"},{"kind":"italic_en","text":"i. q."},{"kind":"text","text":"↓"},{"kind":"arabic","text_bw":"maEomwrN","text_ar":"مَعْمورٌ","orth_type":"arrow"},{"kind":"text","text":". (O, TA.) [See also"},{"kind":"arabic","text_bw":"EumoraAnN","text_ar":"عُمْرَانٌ"},{"kind":"text","text":".] You say"},{"kind":"arabic","text_bw":"A^aroDN EaAmirapN","text_ar":"اَرْضٌ عَامِرَةٌ"},{"kind":"italic_en","text":"A land peopled;"},{"kind":"text","text":"["},{"kind":"italic_en","text":"colonized; cultivated; &c."},{"kind":"text","text":"] (TA.) [See"},{"kind":"arabic","text_bw":"Eamara","text_ar":"عَمَرَ"},{"kind":"text","text":".] And"},{"kind":"arabic","text_bw":"manozilN","text_ar":"مَنْزِلٌ"},{"kind":"arabic","text_bw":"EaAmirN","text_ar":"عَامِرٌ"},{"kind":"italic_en","text":"A place of abode inhabited"},{"kind":"text","text":"[&c.]. (Msb.) And"},{"kind":"arabic","text_bw":"makaAnN EaAmirN","text_ar":"مَكَانٌ عَامِرٌ"},{"kind":"text","text":", and ↓"},{"kind":"arabic","text_bw":"EamiyrN","text_ar":"عَمِيرٌ","orth_type":"arrow"},{"kind":"text","text":", (S, O, TA,) i. e."},{"kind":"arabic","text_bw":"*uw","text_ar":"ذُو"},{"kind":"arabic","text_bw":"EimaArapK","text_ar":"عِمَارَةٍ"},{"kind":"text","text":"["},{"kind":"italic_en","text":"A place inhabited, peopled, well stocked with people and the like, in a flourishing state, in a state the contrary of desolate"},{"kind":"text","text":"or"},{"kind":"italic_en","text":"waste"},{"kind":"text","text":"or"},{"kind":"italic_en","text":"ruined"},{"kind":"text","text":"]. (TA.) ―         -b2-  It is applied also to that which has been a ruin or waste or the like [as meaning"},{"kind":"italic_en","text":"In a state of good repair; in a state the contrary of ruined"},{"kind":"text","text":"or"},{"kind":"italic_en","text":"waste"},{"kind":"text","text":"or"},{"kind":"italic_en","text":"desolate"},{"kind":"text","text":"]; and so ↓"},{"kind":"arabic","text_bw":"maEomuwrN","text_ar":"مَعْمُورٌ","orth_type":"arrow"},{"kind":"text","text":". (S, TA.) [Pl."},{"kind":"arabic","text_bw":"EumoraAnN","text_ar":"عُمْرَانٌ"},{"kind":"text","text":".]       -A3-"},{"kind":"arabic","text_bw":"A_in~ahu laEaAmirN lirab~ihi","text_ar":"اـِنَّهُ لَعَامِرٌ لِرَبِّهِ"},{"kind":"italic_en","text":"Verily he is a server,"},{"kind":"text","text":"or"},{"kind":"italic_en","text":"worshipper, of his Lord."},{"kind":"text","text":"(TA.)       -A4-"},{"kind":"arabic","text_bw":"A^um~u EaAmirK","text_ar":"اُمُّ عَامِرٍ"},{"kind":"text","text":", (S, O, K,) and ↓"},{"kind":"arabic","text_bw":"A^um~u EamorKw","text_ar":"اُمُّ عَمْرٍو","orth_type":"arrow"},{"kind":"text","text":", (K,) but the latter is extr., (TA,)"},{"kind":"italic_en","text":"The hyena;"},{"kind":"text","text":"(S, O, K;) a metonymical surname, (S, O,) determinate, as applying to the species. (TA.) It is said in a prov.,"},{"kind":"arabic","text_bw":"xaAmirY A^um~a EaAmiri A^abo$iriY bijaraAdK EaZolaY wakamari","text_ar":"خَامِرى اُمَّ عَامِرِ اَبْشِرِى بِجَرَادٍ عَظْلَى وَكَمَرِ"},{"kind":"arabic","text_bw":"rijaAlK qatolaY","text_ar":"رِجَالٍ قَتْلَى"},{"kind":"text","text":"["},{"kind":"italic_en","text":"Hide thyself, O Umm-'Ámir: rejoice thou at the news of locusts cohering, and the glands of the penes of slain men:"},{"kind":"text","text":"(in this prov., for"},{"kind":"arabic","text_bw":"kam~i","text_ar":"كَمِّ"},{"kind":"text","text":", in the TA, I have substituted"},{"kind":"arabic","text_bw":"kamarK","text_ar":"كَمَرٍ"},{"kind":"text","text":", which is the reading in variations of the prov.: see Freytag's Arab. Prov., i. 431:)] this being said by a man, [it is asserted that] the animal becomes obsequious to him, so that he muzzles it, and then drags it forth; for the hyena, says Az, is proverbial for its stupidity, and for its being beguiled with soft speech. (TA.) It is called"},{"kind":"arabic","text_bw":"Am~ EAmr","text_ar":"امّ عامر"},{"kind":"text","text":", as though its young one were called"},{"kind":"arabic","text_bw":"EaAmirN","text_ar":"عَامِرٌ"},{"kind":"text","text":", and it is so called by a Hudhalee poet: (L:) or its whelp is called"},{"kind":"arabic","text_bw":"AlEaAmiru","text_ar":"العَامِرُ"},{"kind":"text","text":": (K:) but it is not known with"},{"kind":"arabic","text_bw":"Al","text_ar":"ال"},{"kind":"text","text":"in the compound name with the prefixed noun ["},{"kind":"arabic","text_bw":"Am~","text_ar":"امّ"},{"kind":"text","text":", nor, app., without"},{"kind":"arabic","text_bw":"Am~","text_ar":"امّ"},{"kind":"text","text":"]. (MF, from the Expos. of the"},{"kind":"arabic","text_bw":"dur~ap","text_ar":"دُرَّة"},{"kind":"text","text":".)"}],"source_refs":["TA","S","O","K","L"]}]},"classical_definitions":null}